<DOCNO> AP901212-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
eastern europe generally turned its 
back on the soviet union after the regions communist rulers bowed 
to popular revolt a year ago but trade and geography make the huge 
neighbor impossible to ignore 
new governments must balance the lingering emotion of revolution 
with economic and political reality 
they rejoice over the departure of soviet soldiers and the 
warsaw pacts impending demise but warily watch the floundering 
giant that supplies most of their oil and much of the electricity 
natural gas and timber and buys their mediocre consumer goods 
some east europeans wonder whether they are trading one form of 
domination for another 
it is well known that hungarys energy supplies are largely 
based on soviet raw materials laszlo lengyel an economist and 
political scientist wrote in the hungarian labor daily nepszava 
there is no need for tanks to maintain their influence in the 
region 
anger and distrust toward the soviet union are evident among 
ordinary people throughout the region 
in bulgaria once the kremlins closest ally in the soviet bloc 
only 30 percent of those polled favored close ties with moscow and 
75 percent were against celebrating nov 7 the soviet unions 
revolution day 
in countries where the study of russian was required for 
generations hardly anyone seems to understand it people are 
learning english and german instead 
statues of lenin have come down and places named for soviet 
heroes and their local cohorts have been rechristened 
andras hegedues of hungary the only living signer of the warsaw 
pact feels eastern europeans always must keep their powerful 
neighbor in mind 
even if the soviet union disintegrates russia its largest 
republic will remain a military power he said 
richard sumann director of czechoslovakias foreign investment 
agency said we must prepare for a situation where the soviet 
republics are independent or more independent 
poland czechoslovakia hungary and romania border the soviet 
union bulgaria is tied to the eastern slavs by language and 
custom 
the soviet union says the close ties of four decades were forged 
by more than soviet military might 
eastern europe is eastern europe and it will exist as eastern 
europe forever said oleg a grinevsky the soviet delegate to 
talks on reducing conventional weapons in europe we have 
historic economic and political ties and it is impossible to 
exclude them from everyday life 
in addition to most of its oil hungary gets about onethird of 
its electricity from the soviet union other eastern european 
countries are equally dependent on the soviets with little 
opportunity to change 
cheap and reliable energy supplies are disappearing along with 
soviet political domination beginning in 1991 the soviets will 
demand the market price in dollars for oil delivered to east 
european countries instead of the much lower prices by complex 
agreements within the comecon economic alliance 
several former soviet bloc nations sought oil supplies from 
iraq then the persian gulf crisis tightened supplies and drove 
prices up eastern european countries have pledged to obey the un 
sanctions on iraq 
soviet oil supplies to czechoslovakia this year will be at least 
18 million barrels short of the 116 million promised poland is 
expected to get only 70 million barrels nearly 20 million less 
than expected 
hungary and romania have reeived less electricity from the 
soviet union than anticipated 
the soviet economy is in such chaos that moscow could not even 
promise supplies of chemicals coal timber cellulose paper 
products and consumer goods said laszlo timar who oversees 
hungarys trade with the soviet union 
their problems and troubles are very big and we cannot rely 
on these problems being solved in a short period timar said 
germany is replacing the soviet union as hungarys main trade 
partner but the soviets are not likely to fall below second or 
third he said 
that is a matter of geography according to timar when hungary 
and the others begin paying the world price for soviet oil the 
soviets probably will prefer them as customers because pipelines 
exist to deliver it 
when hungary imposed stiff gasoline price increases in october 
taxi drivers and truckers blocked roads for a weekend virtually 
shutting down the country the government struck a deal with the 
protesters after threatening police or military action 
hegedues who was premier of hungary at the time of the 1956 
uprising against stalinism said he felt civil war was in the 
air during the price protests 
gasoline price increases in czechoslovakia set off two rounds of 
hoarding this year 
czechoslovak officials used looser rules within the soviet union 
to augment their oil supply they cut through the moscow 
bureaucracy to swap trucks buses bulldozers cranes and consumer 
goods for 35 million barrels of oil from the tyumen region of 
siberia 
timar said hungary was close to an agreement to trade its ikarus 
buses for oil 
the soviet union is a huge hungry market for machinery 
manufactured items and consumer goods produced in eastern europe 
beginning jan 1 that trade also will be conducted primarily in 
hard currency 
many of the products canno be sold in the west but east 
european countries need to earn convertible currency from them 
timar estimated hungary will lose 20 to 40 percent of its soviet 
business next year including half of its machinery market because 
soviet customers will be freer to buy from the west 
he predicted hungary will remain a major supplier to the soviet 
union because our products are well known there we think that 
slowly slowly our exports will be increased but they will be 
tragically cut back for the time being 
even though hungarians look west business will draw them east 
he said there is more personal interest in the west now but to 
make money they will travel to moscow 
</TEXT>
