<DOCNO> AP901212-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal investigators studying a huge 
highway pileup reduced the death count from 15 to 13 on wednesday 
and said it was possible a paper mill added to the dense fog blamed 
for the 83car wreck 
the confusion over the number of people killed in tuesdays 
crash on interstate 75 stemmed from problems identifying the 
victims said robert barlett who heads the national transportation 
safety board probe 
more than 50 people were injured in the pileup about 40 miles 
north of chattanooga federal investigators did not expect to find 
more victims barlett said at a news conference in nearby 
cleveland 
the pileup was caused by two separate chainreaction crashes in 
the same spot of the interstate investigators first estimated 75 
vehicles were involved and raised the count to 83 on wednesday 
the lead vehicle in the accident on the southbound side of the 
road apparently was a truck that had slowed down and was rearended 
by another truck said barlett a car apparently was the lead 
vehicle in the crash on the northbound side he said 
this was a most unusual fog very intense very difficult to 
see through said barlett he said a fog warning light had been 
turned on for southbound lanes but not for northbound traffic 
investigators planned to conduct more interviews thursday said 
barlett he said videotapes and computers would be used to help 
reconstruct the crash 
ntsb vice chairman susan coughlin said earlier that 
investigators would be looking at weather highway design driver 
response and environmental factors 
workers removed the last of the wreckage from the scene 
wednesday but the southbound lanes remained closed 
the rolling stretch of highway has a history of fogrelated 
accidents and is just north of the hiwassee river where bowater 
southern industries operates a paper mill east of the highway 
ms coughlin said investigators would talk to officials at 
bowater and other plants about industrys possible contribution to 
the fog 
but she emphasized that the query was just one part of the 
agencys investigation which she said would take six to nine 
months to complete 
to even speculate on anyones involvement at this point would 
simply be prejudicial ms coughlin said 
a 1978 study done by the university of tennessee after a similar 
accident involving 62 vehicles concluded that the primary source 
of fog appeared to be the bowater paper plant 
wayne davis a civil engineer who directed the study said 
wednesday that a paper plant by its nature contributes to fog 
problems 
a paper plant is a process where you take wood cook it and 
evaporate the water to make paper davis said a tremendous 
amount of water is converted into steam if you look around the 
nation you will always find the potential for dense fog around 
paper plants 
bowater spokeswoman astrid sheil said bowater considered that 
study flawed and that tuesday mornings weather conditions could 
have occurred whether the paper plant was nearby or not 
the weather conditions with the inversion from the hot air 
during the day time and the cold ground trapped the fog in said 
ms sheil that is well documented and thats a natural 
phenomenon that happens at this time of year especially in these 
areas 
at least 51 people were taken to hospitals after the crash and 
the tennessee emergency management agency treated others at the 
scene six people remained in critical condition wednesday night 
for three minutes after i stopped cars kept hitting each 
other virgil metts who escaped serious injury told the 
chattanooga newsfree press they kept driving into the fog at 60 
mph 
it was deadly silent a real eerie silence you couldnt see 
anything because of the fog and all you heard was exploding gas 
tanks 
george and margaret dawson were in the southbound lanes tuesday 
in a van packed with valuables for their retirement move from 
michigan to florida 
seconds later those valuables were scattered across the 
highway 
the whole back of the van is gone mrs dawson said but 
after seeing some of the other people we consider ourselves lucky 
what a way to start retirement 
</TEXT>
