<DOCNO> AP901212-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the case of a badly beaten 3yearold boy who died 
after being dumped near a bayfront home has generated new alarm 
about floridas childprotection system 
the state passed childabuse reforms and boosted spending after 
last years widely publicized death of 2yearold bradley mcgee 
who was under state supervision but was returned home in spite of 
reports of abuse he died from being dunked repeatedly into a 
toilet because he had soiled his pants 
four state social services workers were charged in that case 
one was convicted of felony child abuse for negligence and placed 
on three years probation 
the latest case involved a boy who was returned to his mothers 
custody after she left him with a sitter for three months 
chief dade juvenile judge william gladstone summoned state 
social services officials to a hearing friday to find out what 
happened to the boy initially known as baby lollipops 
he was told of a lack of training and crushing caseloads the 
boys caseworker had 50 children compared with a national standard 
of 12 per childprotection caseworker 
this case is my failure too gladstone said his eyes 
tearing we all failed somehow this child was killed and he 
was killed by every person in this state 
baby lollipops was found nov 2 beside a wall around a bayfront 
miami beach home the extensive injuries and severe neglect 
including a daysold diaper held with packing tape were 
incomprehensible said police detective tom hoolahan 
before the boys identity was determined officers named the 
victim after the lollipops on his tshirt 
dade countys medical examiner dr joseph davis said monday it 
was the worst case of child abuse he has ever seen in 34 years in 
the office 
the boys mother and her female lover were arrested dec 5 on 
firstdegree murder charges 
police said the mother ana marie cardona admitted she and 
girlfriend olivia gonzalez 24 left the boy in a yard in an 
upscale neighborhood hoping he would be found by a wealthy family 
they fled with two other children to the orlando area 
the boy wasnt found for four days 
it turned out the boy was lazaro figueroa who with his sister 
had been placed under state supervision two years earlier that was 
after their mother left them with a baby sitter and didnt return 
for three months authorities said lazaros father was a drug 
dealer killed four weeks before his birth 
the children were returned to ms cardona now 29 because there 
was no evidence of abuse the state health and rehabilitative 
services department said however ms cardona and her three 
children the department wasnt aware of the third subsequently 
moved and the agency lost track 
the caseworker didnt report ms cardonas disappearance to the 
court for four months 
the caseworker has not been charged 
department spokesman steve konicki said criticism of the 
caseworker was unfair because at the time she was hired the state 
had no training for childprotection workers the worker wasnt 
aware at the time the mother moved that she should go to court and 
seek a police pickup order 
the caseworker tried diligently on her own to locate the family 
konicki said but simply hadnt been properly trained she had been 
since he said 
