<TEXT>
fiftyfive pilot whales beached 
themselves near the kennedy family compound tuesday and rescuers 
managed to get fewer than 10 headed out to sea before deciding to 
kill many of he mammals to end their suffering 
volunteers struggled throughout the day to save the creatures 
most of them mothers and calves with little success 
they splashed the beached whales with water and soothed them 
with wet towels the whales up to 20 feet long and 3000 pounds 
were listless with eyes closed making squeaking and whistling 
sounds and occasionally twitching 
im offering a little comfort said one volunteer karen 
kelly they respond to your touch and your voice they are scared 
and they dont know whats going on 
say a prayer she added 
by midnight two whales had been moved to an aquarium eight or 
nine had been seen swimming away and the rest were either drowning 
as the tide rose or being injected with a lethal chemical the 
volunteers were sent home and the wouldbe rescuers expected all 
the whales to be dead by morning either from drowning or the 
lethal injections 
scientists decided on euthanasia becuase the airbreathing 
animals were too weak to swim away on the rising tide and drowned 
as they submerged the whales suffering was worsened because 
without being immersed in cooling water their body temperatures 
rose 
experts were unable to explain why the whales beached 
themselves 
about 100 volunteers endured high wind and 35degree 
temperatures in the futile effort to save the whales they used 
stretchers to return nine of the whales to open water but one was 
believed to have beached itself again 
the whales got stuck in shallow pools at low tide at squaw 
island said ian mcmillan associate director of the cape cod 
aquarium 
on the beach a few floodlights and car headlights illuminated 
the moonless night ruben baker a volunteer said the subfreezing 
temperatures didnt spoil his enthusiasm for the task 
you get a really neat feeling from the whales baker said 
these whales could pick you up and throw you through the air but 
it feels like they know were trying to help them 
theyre sort of flopping around said roger cadrin a 
lieutenant with the hyannis fire department who helped free a few 
of the animals we named ours betsy and there was bob scraps a 
few others when we let them go they were all pointing in the same 
direction they were all anxious to go they were happy to get 
moving 
two freed whales have radio transmitters attached to their tails 
and were followed by marine experts in an inflatable boat they 
also have luminescent tags attached to their fins so they can be 
seen at night 
mcmillan said it was unusual for whales to beach on the southern 
side of cape cod 
historically its been on the other side he said there 
are certain areas where they seem to strand time and time again 
dave wiley of the international wildlife coalition which 
assisted in the rescue said the test for the freed whales was 
whether they remain at sea or beach themselves again 
the rescue effort was the first test of a 600person volunteer 
whale rescue program set up by the new england aquarium two years 
ago mcmillan said 
it was the first mass beaching in the area since 70 pilot 
whales a small type of whale beached at several spots four years 
ago three young whales that beached on the cape three years ago 
were rescued and returned to the sea 
some scientists speculate that the beachings occur when the pod 
or group of whales follows a sick leader ashore or that the 
mammals become disoriented by magnetic variations along geological 
faults 
mcmillan said aquarium scientists are working on a theory that 
high tides can cause beachings planetary alignments last week 
caused the highest tides in 60 years 
whales may use current flows to navigate and they may get 
confused by a change in the flow that you only see in very high 
tides mcmillan said 
whales give out heat in only three places the dorsal fin the 
tail and around the flippers the system is designed to conserve 
body heat in the water so when they come onto land the whales cook 
inside 
some of their extremities could be freezing because of the 
cold weather and at they same time they overheat internally 
mcmillan said when this happens their body chemistry goes beyond 
any limits that are considered treatable or recoverable 
