<TEXT>
the international monetary fund is cutting its 
loan interest rate in a move that could save debtor countries about 
100 million a year sources say 
at the end of october the fund had about 30 billion worth of 
loans outstanding mexico argentina brazil and venezuela are the 
biggest debtors among 78 borrowing countries 
the fund with headquarters in washington is owned by 154 
countries with the united states the largest contributor 
the interest that the fund charges is based on rates that five 
major governments the united states japan germany britain and 
france pay on the shortterm bonds they sell to the public the 
fund has been charging 913 percent of this rate which it 
calculates every week 
one source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the funds 
board of executive directors decided monday to cut the proportion 
to 878 percent retroactive to nov 1 the directors met behind 
closed doors and did not announce the change they review the 
formula every three months 
for the week of dec 3 the interest the fund charges to debtors 
had worked out to an annual 827 percent the decision to change 
the formula reduces that by 32 basis points or 32100ths of one 
percent to 795 percent 
on loans of 30 billion such a cut would amount to 100 million 
in savings to debtors if the reduction is maintained for a year 
in recent years the imf has lent largely to third world 
countries in financial trouble to get a loan a government 
promises to change its policies and put itself in better condition 
to repay this involves devaluings its currency reducing subsidies 
on basic goods and cutting spending in many cases 
critics say the price of the promises can be too high greatly 
increased prices and many lost jobs in the borrowing country such 
effects have repeatedly led to bloody riots including in the 
dominican republic last month 
the imf maintains that the pain will be worse if changes are 
delayed 
an arrangement with the fund has often been the seal of 
approval that private banks want to see before making much bigger 
loans of their own 
</TEXT>
