<TEXT>
major discrepancies in the count of soviet 
weapons will delay senate approval of a new treaty slashing 
nonnuclear armaments in europe by at least two months 
congressional sources say 
the kremlin figures understate the total numbers of tanks 
artillery and other conventional weapons the soviets would have to 
destroy under the agreement by tens of thousands the sources 
speaking on condition of anonymity said tuesday 
although the differences involve several weapons the largest 
problem involves tanks the kremlin has been gradually moving tanks 
out of central europe the area controlled by the treaty and 
basing them east of the ural mountains in the soviet union 
some in congress fear that instead of dismantling 10000 to 
20000 tanks as the pact requires the soviets would have to 
destroy few or none 
in a letter to president bush sen jesse helms rnc the 
senior gop member of the senate foreign relations committee 
complained about the wholesale differences in the soviet figures 
the soviets may in fact be defeating the object and purpose 
of the treaty from the outset helms wrote 
the precise numbers of weapons in eac category held by each 
side although they are part of the treaty remain secret 
leaders of the 16member north atlantic treaty organization and 
the sixnation warsaw pact signed the conventional forces in europe 
treaty in paris on nov 19 bush praised the pact then for reducing 
to practically nil the tensions that have existed 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev said instead of 
military force our world order will be based on equitable 
dialogue 
at the same time the us envoy to the negotiations hinted of 
problems underlying the treaty but congressional officials said 
they were not expected to be this large 
we expect and have expected all along with an unprecedented 
data exchange of this sort for there to be mistakes inaccuracies 
incomplete pieces of information said ambassador james woolsey 
the problems were spelled out on monday in a briefing for 
congressional aides by the state and defense departments the cia 
and the arms control and disarmament agency 
they also were the subject of discussions between secretary of 
state james a baker iii and soviet foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze in houston a white house source said 
several democratic staff sources said the problems are 
correctable and should not derail eventual senate approval of the 
treaty which had been planned to be one of the first items of 
business when the new congress convenes in january 
the discrepancies occur at a time when the united states and the 
soviet union are enjoying their warmest relations in four decades 
under the treatys terms each side has 90 days until feb 19 
to correct inaccurate data 
now a republican source said the administration will not 
submit the treaty for ratification until march because of the 
accounting problems 
in addition to the undercounting of tanks the soviet data 
understate numbers of armored personnel carriers by 12000 
artillery pieces by 10000 and combat aircraft by about 3000 
according to administration calculations 
one democratic source said the problem arose in part because 
us negotiators had been working from 1989 weapons lists provided 
by the soviets between the time the lists were provided and the 
treaty was put in final form the soviets already had withdrawn as 
many as 20000 tanks from the area governed by the treaty to east 
of the ural mountains 
the senior democratic aide said the situation was viewed as an 
accounting problem and that such numbers discrepancies are not 
unusual in the field of arms control 
last year as us negotiators prepared their own numbers they 
discovered 900 tanks they didnt know the united states had in 
europe the source said some 750 of those excess tanks have since 
been transferred to egypt in a move not unlike what the soviets 
apparently have done he said 
the 160page treaty limits each side to 20000 main battle 
tanks 30000 armored combat vehicles 20000 artillery pieces 
6800 fighter planes and 2000 combat helicopters 
each side has 40 months to reduce its armaments to the ceilings 
spelled out in the treaty which covers a 25 million square mile 
area stretching from the atlantic ocean to the ural mountains 
