<TEXT>
president bush is renominating a banking 
regulator who has been criticized for creating a credit shortage by 
cracking down too hard on institutions with sour real estate loans 
the white house said tuesday that bush planned to appoint robert 
l clarke to a second fiveyear term as comptroller of the 
currency the regulator of nationally chartered banks he must be 
confirmed by the senate 
according to government and industry sources who spoke 
anonymously last week white house chief of staff john sununu had 
sought to block the nomination 
sununus home state of new hampshire where he served as 
governor has been particularly hard hit by the socalled credit 
crunch 
according to a government source white house aides last week 
began soliciting criticism of clarke from bank and business 
executives after receiving a letter of complaint from major 
republican contributors 
bankers and borrowers in the northeast have been saying for a 
year that clarkes examiners have overreacted to the savings and 
loan crisis discouraging bankers from making even sound loans 
however clarke and other regulators maintained that they have 
not tightened standards inappropriately they blame banks 
reluctance to lend on deteriorating real estate markets and on a 
lack of loan demand resulting from the sluggish economy 
clarke had the backing of treasury secretary nicholas f brady 
a longtime friend of the president the secretary is the 
comptrollers boss but in practice the comptroller has 
considerable independence 
after reports of sununus opposition were published democratic 
and republican members of the house banking committee rushed to 
clarkes defense they warned that the white house would be sending 
the wrong signal to regulators if they failed to reappoint a 
regulator for being too tough 
although clarke jokingly embraced the nickname regulator from 
hell he has since moderated his public remarks 
in a statement thanking bush for the reappointment he said 
we can work through the current problems if lenders assume their 
responsibility to make loans and take reasonable risks and if 
regulators follow a responsive balanced approach that takes into 
account the very significant national interest in not 
unnecessarily depressing credit availability 
i believe that now is a time for the application of common 
sense a time when neither lenders nor regulators should overreact 
or be unresponsive he said 
national banks which are chartered by the federal government 
are about a third of the nations commercial banks the rest are 
chartered by the states national banks tend to be larger and 
together account for more than half of commercial bank assets 
</TEXT>
