<TEXT>
most state insurance departments are spending 
more money to investigate consumer complaints but some cant keep 
pace because of budget problems says a new report 
spending on consumer services rose an average of 12 percent from 
1989 to 1990 says the report prepared by a consumer organization 
and several insurance industry groups and released tuesday but the 
study found wide variations in spending levels 
state insurance budgets for consumer services ranged from 38 in 
michigan for every 1000 people to a high of 712 in delaware 
massachusetts spends about 60 per 1000 people on consumer 
services while washington state spends 444 
the average is 230 per 1000 people in the 36 states that 
provided the information the study found 
the good news is that most departments offer many services to 
consumers said stephen brobeck executive director of the 
consumer federation of america 
but states such as michigan and massachusetts have undergone 
statewide budget cuts that have hurt consumer services the report 
said michigans tollfree phone for insurance complaints was 
discontinued a number of years ago staff size has been cut in 
half 
there is a largescale demand for our services which we are 
not encouraging or tapping acknowledged howard spence 
michigans deputy insurance commissioner 
despite the cuts michigan recovers more than 2 million a year 
for consumers through the complaint process spence said 
despite the budget cuts in massachusetts the state managed to 
recover 600000 last year for consumers 
the bestrun consumer services programs according to the 
report 
florida with a substantial population of elderly residents 
spends 567 for each 1000 people 
new york with a 55 million budget for consumer services in 
1990 the largest of any state that comes out to 307 per 1000 
population 
texas which receives almost onequarter of the 2 million 
requests made each year to state insurance departments for 
information about the industry 
delaware which funnels 90 percent of its budget for consumer 
services into handling complaints the remainder goes for 
information and education programs 
kansas and wisconsin which each spent more than 1 million 
this year for consumer services 
half of the states responding to the survey have a tollfree 
telephone hotline for complaints about insurance 
more than 40 percent of the states distribute information about 
insurance pricing the insolvency of some insurers and whether 
there are large numbers of complaints against a particular company 
large states such as pennsylvania spend a relatively small 
amount on consumer services 19 million which comes out to 158 
per 1000 people but employees in other parts of the state 
insurance department take consumer inquiries pointed out amy 
dugan a spokeswoman for the agency 
state insurance departments set rates approve mergers 
investigate consumer complaints and have the power to revoke 
licenses of insurance companies federal law leaves all insurance 
regulation to the states 
the study was prepared by the consumer insurance interest group 
the national association of professional insurance agents the 
american insurance association and the american council of life 
insurance the consumer group includes the consumer federation of 
america public citizen and the national insurance consumer 
organization 
