<TEXT>
the publisher of the new york daily news says the 
tabloid will keep plowing ahead as long as it is gaining ground 
against an employee strike a move a union spokesman called sheer 
masochism 
publisher james f hoge made the announcement tuesday after a 
board meeting of the news parent the tribune co some wall street 
analysts had speculated the board would close the paper and cut its 
losses 
our rule is that we are plowing ahead as long was we can show 
that we are making significant progress hoge said 
theodore kheel the striking unions legal adviser countered 
the decision is a form of sheer masochism 
the news has no hope of survival whatsoever in the absence of 
a settlement or sale he said the sooner the board realizes 
that the better everyone including the tribune co will be 
the news using managers replacements and employees transferred 
from other tribune co newspapers has continued to publish despite 
the 7weekold strike by 2100 employees in nine unions 
negotiators for both sides arrived in washington today at the 
federal mediation and conciliation service which is trying to end 
the sixweekold strike 
members of the negotiation teams began arriving at the services 
headquarters shortly after 9 am but declined to comment on the 
talks they met with bernard e delury director of the service 
and other mediators 
hoge said the news is regaining strength daily and increased net 
paid circulation by 28000 to 580000 since the end of last week 
through a network of dealers and hawkers now totaling almost half 
the prestrike number of 12000 outlets 
the paper had daily circulation of 109 million copies before 
the strike began on oct 25 
it is the opinion of everyone involved in this process that we 
are making significant progress and we are going forward hoge 
said 
the publisher said the strike is costly but not as expensive 
as trying to run the paper with all the excess costs and contract 
abuses that we had in the old contract 
hoge said the paper is losing money but could be profitable if 
the company reaches reasonable settlements with the unions he said 
he is confident many advertisers who left for rival tabloids will 
return as circulation increases 
about 100 people most from various chicago unions picketed the 
tribune tower on tuesday led by several of the striking daily news 
workers tribune co also publishes the chicago tribune 
</TEXT>
