dec 6 
the chattanooga tenn times on china 
only 18 months since china massacred prodemocracy demonstrators 
in tiananmen square president bush was meeting at the white house 
with chinas foreign minister and us ambassador to china john 
lilley was recently in seattle chastising demonstrators against 
chinas gross violations of human rights 
what is going on 
never mind that china has shown no remorse for its massacre of 
innocents but has continued to persecute those involved in the 
prodemocracy movement bush counted on the shift of public 
interest to the middle east as a cover for reopening the door of 
the white house to beijing but not everyone was looking the other 
way 
confronted by demonstrators against chinas humanrights abuses 
lilley got into a shouting match calling them cowards and 
ridiculously suggesting that if they hadnt been at tiananmen 
square they had no right to protest he even shouted at a tibetan 
man that he should go back to china and serve china 
the ambassador has since admitted he made a mistake but 
defended himself by saying he was provoked by namecalling from 
some of the demonstrators that is no excuse any diplomat so 
easily pushed to the point of losing control should be in another 
line of work 
in light of the administrations weakkneed response to chinas 
brutal repression of internal dissent lilley should have been 
prepared to take his lumps from demonstrators rightly protesting 
beijings humanrights abuses an apology is clearly called for 
but was conspicuously absent from the ambassadors statement 
admitting error and the white house has been silent derelict in 
its duty at least to reprimand lilley for his unseemly and 
unwarranted outburst but that we suppose should come as no 
surprise 
 
dec 7 
le monde paris on the persian gulf 
saddam hussein has finally accomplished one of the gestures that 
the international community ordered of him four months ago his 
decision to free all the hostages without delay or conditions and 
no longer as he previously announced between dec 25 and march 25 
was swallowed dec 7 by the parliament in baghdad 
if this initiative which puts an end to a long scandal 
shouldnt reward him with any gratitude it nonetheless marks a 
political retreat for the first time since the annexation of 
kuwait the iraqi dictator has satisfied one of the principal 
demands of the united nations 
in the eyes of the united states and its allies the fate of the 
hostages and in particular the fear of taking the lives of these 
human shields dispersed on the strategic sites of the host 
country never played the deterrent role that baghdad expected 
hostages or not nothing has stopped a logic of war from 
unfolding in the gulf and the western military detachment 
reinforced at the end of the month is from now on credible in 
these conditions saddam hussein has judged it more useful to grant 
freedom to his hostages 
 
dec 7 
la repubblica rome on the persian gulf 
for the first time since aug 2 the day of the iraqi invasion 
of kuwait it is right to say that the caravan of peace has started 
to move in the arabian desert 
if saddam hussein seriously intends to liberate the thousands of 
americans western europeans and russians who until now have been 
used as human shields and if this is not the strategy of a 
crafty merchant trying to gain time and divide his adversaries 
then the bloodbath in the persian gulf is not the one and only 
inevitable conclusion to the crisis 
 
dec 9 
the observer london on trade talks 
removing barriers to trade in manufactured goods has led to an 
immense growth in world commerce in the postwar years 
trade has kept growing even at times of economic difficulty yet 
now european and american leaders seem incapable of pursuing a 
broad common interest even though they know its longterm benefit 
to both their own countries and the world community to be beyond 
doubt 
the persian gulf crisis has revealed the reluctance of most of 
americas european allies for vigorous cooperation now that the 
cold war is over 
if rich europe relapses into selfish regionalism it will find 
itself paying a price its prosperity and stability are bound to 
lure the less fortunate 
there is already alarm over the flow of illegal immigrants from 
north africa the collapse of communist border controls in east 
europe has made it easier for asians to slip unnoticed into the 
west 
it is time for western leaders to show they recognize the 
responsibilities beyond their own parish 
 
dec 9 
