israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir told 
members of congress today he firmly supports president bushs 
decision to ease trade with the soviet union as a reward for its 
liberalized policies 
israel and its supporters in congress had spearheaded opposition 
to trade concessions for the soviets but are now trying to help the 
strapped soviet economy since the relaxation of restrictions on 
jewish emigration 
shamir spoke to the senate foreign relations committee in a 
closed session but israeli officials relayed the gist of his 
remarks 
shamir was meeting later in the day with soviet foreign minister 
eduard shevardnadze the hastily scheduled meeting requested by 
the soviets and arranged by the state department reflects the 
fastimproving relationship between the two countries 
before meeting shamir shevardnadze is calling on president 
bush who has been weighing how to ease immediate soviet food 
shortages and to help the economy in the longer term bush has 
decided to temporarily waive the 1974 jacksonvanik amendment which 
limits trade with the soviets unless they allow free emigration 
we think it the amendment could be dispensed with for a year 
or more because of the very liberalized policies related to the 
emigration of soviet jews shamir told reporters at a conference 
of the american enterprise institute 
gorbachev has been allowing jews out at a rate of 1000 to 2000 
a day a far cry from the virtually closed gates of the soviet 
union through most of the 1970s and 1980s 
the subject of the flood of immigrants is expected to come up 
with shevardnadze shamir said as well as israels request for 
direct flights from the soviet union and its desire for resumption 
of full diplomatic ties which the soviets broke in 1967 
the crisis in the persian gulf and prospects for israeliarab 
peace talks are also expected to come up said other officials 
the session with shamir will give shevardnadze an opportunity to 
try to persuade him that an international peace conference could 
help settle the arabisraeli dispute 
but shamir said israel will not participate in such a 
conference and israel will not accept imposed solutions 
instead israel wants direct talks with its arab neighbors as 
outlined in a fourpoint peace plan shamir proposed last year and 
the united states endorsed 
peace plans are neither fashions nor automobiles we must not 
introduce a new model every year shamir said 
israel also has not changed its mind about excluding the 
palestine liberation organization from peace talks and it hopes 
the plos support for iraq has convinced the world of its 
unsuitability as a peace partner shamir said 
sounding a conciliatory tone the prime minister said israel 
wants to cooperate with its arab neighbors on an arms control plan 
that would rid the volatile middle east of its vast arsenals of 
arms 
israel also wants to cooperate on a plan to ease the reigons 
increasingly severe water shortages he said 
he pledged again that israel would refrain from a preemptive 
strike against iraq unless attacked 
