<TEXT>
two california communities are 
being challenged by the american civil liberties union to remove 
religious symbols that mark the holiday season from public 
property 
in beverly hills the american jewish congress and four jewish 
residents backed by the aclu filed a lawsuit in federal court 
seeking the removal of a 28foot hannukah menorah displayed at a 
municipal park 
in monterey the aclu has demanded that the city remove a 
nativity scene from the city hall lawn by thursday or face a 
lawsuit 
the civil liberties union contends the displays amount to a 
government endorsement of religion but the communities say they 
are celebrating the diversity of religious beliefs in the nation by 
offering space for holiday displays from a variety of groups 
chabad a movement of hasidic jews installed the large 
candelabra in beverly hills on monday for public celebration of the 
eightday jewish holiday 
the suit filed by the american jewish congress contends the 
menorah on public property violates the first amendments guarantee 
of separation of church and state 
carol plotkin of the jewish congress argued that religious 
freedom is best preserved by banning all religious objects on 
public lands 
there are plenty of opportunities to put up creches or 
menorahs or any other religious object on private property 
government should be free of any religious objects she said 
city attorney greg stepanicich defended the citys approval of 
the chabad menorah 
we have a lighted christmas tree a lighted seasons 
greetings sign and now weve allowed the menorah as part of that 
overall holiday message stepanicich said 
he said that state and federal courts have allowed religious 
