<TEXT>
young people who undergo surgery to repair one of 
the most common birth defects of the heart can look forward to 
normal life spans a 30year follow up shows 
the study which looked at people who had been operated on for a 
problem called atrial septal defect showed that those who were 
under age 25 went on to live just as long as those with healthy 
hearts 
older people did not do as well but surgery still makes sense 
for these people because the outlook for survival is still far 
better than for those who didnt undergo the operation 
the study published in thursdays new england journal of 
medicine was based on the experiences of the first 123 patients 
who had the operation at the mayo clinic between 1956 and 1960 
atrial septal defect is the technical name for a kind of hole in 
an interior wall of the heart in this abnormality blood 
improperly flows from the hearts left upper pumping chamber into 
the right the defect is often discovered in late childhood and 
symptoms can include trouble breathing fatigue and chest 
palpitations 
the study found that 97 percent of those who were under age 11 
at the time of the operation and 93 percent of those between ages 
12 and 24 were still alive 30 to 34 years later this was not 
significantly different from a comparison group with healthy 
hearts 
from the perspective of employment and insurability such 
patients should be strongly reassured wrote dr joseph g murphy 
and colleagues 
however among those between ages 25 and 41 survival was 84 
percent while 91 percent in this age category in the comparison 
group were still alive survival among those over age 41 was worse 
still 40 percent among the heart patients and 59 percent in the 
comparison group 
the longterm results of repair at older ages are unfavorable 
as compared with those of correction at earlier ages they wrote 
but this does not mean that older patients shouldnt have the 
surgery 
other studies have shown that the outlook is grim for those who 
do not get the defect fixed by age 50 threequarters are dead 
and by age 60 90 percent are dead 
atrial septal defects account for between 7 percent and 10 
percent of all genetic malformations of the heart 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

