<TEXT>
mounting discontent and a ruined economy 
are forcing reform in albania europes last bastion of stalinism 
where leaders are buying time by making surprising concessions 
three days of student protest in the albanian capital tirana 
prompted the startling decision tuesday by the ruling communists to 
permit other political movements five members of the 13member 
ruling politburo also were dropped and government changes promised 
the decisions came just before president ramiz alia head of 
state and of the ruling albanian labor party met a group of the 
striking students urging them to return to class and to work 
peacefully within the law for the reforms they seek 
students on wednesday announced formation of the countrys first 
noncommunist party the democratic party of albania to the cheers 
of crowds in the capital a witness reported 
albania has a turbulent history for centuries it was dominated 
by italian or ottoman turkish rulers and it gained true 
independence only after world war ii under the stalinist enver 
hoxha 
alia who took over when hoxha died in 1985 appears to be 
trying to contain an explosion of popular anger with swift 
political maneuvering and timely concessions 
in july he defused the most serious crisis to date allowing 
thousands of albanians jammed into foreign embassies in tirana to 
emigrate and reshuffling the leadership to offer the public 
scapegoats to blame for political repression and economic misery 
wage increases also were promised but albanians say they have 
not materialized 
but this afforded only temporary respite from the leaders basic 
dilemma how to make the changes needed to get the economy going 
while retaining control and avoiding open rebellion 
at a communist party meeting last month premier adil carcani 
painted a picture of catastrophe in the economy alia bluntly told 
workers on nov 29 that the economy is on the brink of a state of 
emergency 
the drought has severely curbed electric supplies mainly 
generated from hydroelectric stations in the countrys rugged 
mountains and affected crops grown on the fertile coatal plains 
the students protest that brought this weeks historic changes 
reportedly began with demands for more heat and light in their 
wintry tirana dormitories 
alia has attempted to ease food shortages particularly of meat 
by allowing private shops that sell at two or three times the state 
prices he has also promised imports of food and other items but 
lacks the necessary hard currency to carry out the pledge 
isolated for decades albania is also seeking foreign 
investment as alia himself warned the students tuesday that wont 
come if there is political instability 
but there is much cause for discontent in towns most homes are 
in slumlike threestory apartment blocks factories are outdated 
and extremely dilapidated in the countryside children trudge 
miles to school while women tend fields with primitive picks and 
hoes 
most albanians seem to express their disgust with this state of 
affairs by working less and less ignoring the leaderships many 
appeals to toil for economic improvement 
but a leadership steeped in decades of authoritarian rule is 
finding it hard to adjust to the new changes 
it remains to be seen whether any new political parties will be 
allowed to contest scheduled parliamentary elections in february 
the communists have made no mention of giving up their 
constitutional monopoly on power 
also a population unused to democracy might find it difficult 
to organize any opposition to the communists who have dominated 
public life since taking power in 1944 
students were a powerful force behind many of eastern europes 
revolutions last year and are among the few groups in albania who 
have the courage and unity to challenge the communists 
with the highest birth rate in europe albania is a country of 
young people about 75 percent of its 32 million people are under 
40 they learn about the outside world from television broadcasts 
from neighboring yugoslavia greece and italy and from the 
albanianlanguage service of voice of america 
this contact with the outside world and the reforms made this 
year have emboldened the young who do not have the deeply 
instilled fear of those who survived hoxhas harsh rule 
 
</TEXT>
