<TEXT>
atampt and mci agreed wednesday to settle 
lawsuits that charged false advertising and customer theft and 
proposed new federal standards to prevent consumers from being 
switched from one longdistance company to another against their 
will 
american telephone amp telegraph co and mci communications corp 
which had sued one another over their multimilliondollar ad 
campaigns agreed to settle the suits out of court along with an 
atampt suit against mci and its telemarketing agent that alleged 
false and deceptive sales practices 
terms of the agreement were not disclosed 
mci spokeswoman pam small said company officials were bound by 
the agreement not to comment on the settlement 
but lest anyone think the two arch rivals were going to 
discontinue their allout scrap for new customers she said were 
still competitors 
and atampt spokesman herb linnen said his company will continue 
to pursue customers and try to retain existing ones with the same 
resourcefulness and aggressiveness we have pursued in the past 
that has included negative ad campaigns in which customers 
are shown getting fed up with sales pitches from mci or skits in 
which they declare competing longdistance companies should put 
their claims of lower prices and better service in writing 
but linnen said atampt wanted to get beyond the recent legal 
squabbling which he said is really not good for either atampt or 
mci or for the customer 
as part of the agreement the two companies agreed to propose to 
the federal communications commission industrywide standards to 
help prevent unauthorized switching of customers by longdistance 
companies 
state and federal authorities and local phone companies have 
received tens of thousands of complaints about unauthorized 
switching 
the proposed standards would permit switches only by one of the 
following means 
a customerinitiated call to an 800 number of the carrier to 
which the customer is switching 
independent thirdparty confirmation 
signed letter of authorization 
a call placed by the customer to their local or longdistance 
telephone company 
atampt which had claimed it was losing customers because of 
unauthorized switching by mci and its telemarketing agent had 
asked the fcc in january to require a customers written 
authorization before a switch could be made current rules require 
only that a longdistance company be able to present if demanded 
by a local phone company written authorization from a customer 
linnen said atampt still considered written preauthorization the 
best method but since the fcc has not acted atampt thought the 
compromise was better than waiting for the perfect solution that 
might never arrive 
the two companies along with us sprint have been locked in a 
fierce battle for customers atampt and mci or their agents have 
been placing calls to millions of phone users each month trying to 
get them to switch their longdistance service 
since the breakup of the old bell system in 1984 atampts share 
of the longdistance market has fallen to below 70 percent mci 
the nations second largest longdistance carrier now has about 15 
percent of the market 
mci had sued atampt in us district court in washington on oct 
10 1989 alleging false and deceptive advertising practices atampt 
countersued on oct 26 
on jan 10 this year atampt sued mci and its telemarketing agent 
in newark nj federal court alleging false and deceptive 
telemarketing practices 
both sides denied any wrongdoing and no dollar amounts were 
specified in the suits 
</TEXT>
