<TEXT>
thousands of albanians chanting 
democracy democracy on wednesday hailed the foundation of the 
tiny stalinist countrys first noncommunist political party 
albanians reached by telephone said thousands of people surged 
into university square in tirana albanias capital to support 
students who won unprecedented concessions from the communist 
leadership in several days of protests 
the developments appeared to herald the end of oneparty rule 
not only in the balkan nation but in all of europe albania a 
country of just over 3 million has been the last on the continent 
to cling to oneparty communist rule 
president ramiz alia addressed the nation late wednesday and 
asked for calm 
he called on the political and patriotic conscience of you all 
to avoid mistakes which could have consequences for the entire 
country his taped radio message was monitored by the british 
broadcasting corp in london 
alia and his communist leadership declared tuesday that they 
would allow formation of noncommunist parties in albania which 
was isolated for decades by its hardline rulers 
the crowds cheered wildly wednesday as students and others 
announced formation of the democratic party of albania according 
to a tirana engineer reached by telephone from vienna 
zamira koleze a reporter for albanias official radio said 
students would try to register the party thursday at the ministry 
of justice 
the huge peaceful crowd chanted demcoracy democracy we 
want albania to be like europe and we want democratic 
albania the engineer said he spoke on condition of anonymity 
there was also a cheer for alia for allowing alternative 
political parties the engineer said 
an editor for the official ata news agency said those who 
attended the rally filled a big field as well as nearby hillsides 
and the staircases of a student residence 
it was without disorder completely regular koleze said 
it all went well when it was over everyone returned to their 
homes 
estimatesof the number of people who rallied ranged from 10000 
to 100000 
alia who has been seeking to slowly introduce moderate reforms 
succeeded tuesday in ousting five hardline members of the 
13member ruling politburo of the communist party he called on 
premier adil carcani to reshuffle the government as well 
the communist party formally called the albanian labor party 
decided to hold a national meeting dec 26 the meeting is to work 
out the partys electoral platform but it could also make more 
leadership changes 
the engineer said the new opposition partys guiding committee 
would meet soon to choose a leader he said the party intended to 
contest parliamentary elections scheduled for feb 10 
but it was not immediately clear whether the communists would 
allow the party to take part 
last month the legislature adopted a new election law 
permitting more than one candidate but officials said then that 
pluralism would not be permitted 
alia told representatives of the students he met with tuesday 
that any new political organization would have to apply for 
registration with the justice ministry 
alia previously rejected the type of democratic reforms that 
swept communists from power in eastern europe last year 
on tuesday he appealed to the police as well as the students to 
act correctly in a civilized and democratic way ata reported 
the engineer indicated the people who attended the rally also 
wanted to avoid bloodshed 
we want to go ahead without blood absolutely without blood 
all will be solved by speaking and by discussion he said 
since assuming power in 1985 after the death of his predecessor 
and albanias founder enver hoxha alia has sought to lead his 
country out of selfimposed isolation establishing diplomatic 
relations with dozens of countries and seeking to renew ties with 
the superpowers 
wednesdays mass rally followed four days of protest by students 
and weekend clashes with police in which several people were 
injured and some arrested reports that one or more people may have 
been killed could not be confirmed 
students who boycotted classes this week after sundays 
violence returned to classes wednesday according to an official 
reached by telephone from vienna he also spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
the albanian official said there were no reports of unrest 
elsewhere in the country 
the student demonstrations were the first known major opposition 
to the communist leadership since july when thousands of albanians 
stormed foreign embassies and refused to leave until they were 
granted permission to emigrate 
on tuesday about 10000 people who gathered in the university 
quarter welcomed the announcement that pluralism would be permitted 
with chants of down with the dictatorship long live 
freedom and long live democracy the austria press agency 
reported 
an italian member of the european parliament visiting albania 
alexander langer told apa in a telephone interview that officials 
were becoming increasingly pluralistic by the hour this appears 
to reflect what is happening 
