<TEXT>
the food and drug administration said 
wednesday it will soon impose minimum quality standards for medical 
gloves worn by health care workers to protect themselves agaist 
aids and other diseases 
the federal centers for disease control in atlanta recommends 
that physicians dentists and other health care workers wear 
protective rubber or plastic gloves 
under current fda regulations manufacturers of medical gloves 
conduct their own testing the fda had no standard it could 
enforce 
new regulations published in wednesdays federal register and 
scheduled to go into effect in 90 days will standardize the 
testing and define the failure rates the agency said 
it said gloves that do not meet the standards will be seized if 
necessary to keep them off the market 
as part of the new testing the agency said randomly selected 
samples of gloves will be examined for tears holes and any foreign 
matter embedded in the gloves the gloves will also be filled with 
about a quart of water and checked for leaks 
sale for medical uses will be forbidden for batches of gloves if 
leaks are found in more than 25 per 1000 for surgeons gloves and 
40 per 1000 for patientexamination gloves surgeons gloves were 
given a stricter standard because they are in contact with a 
patients blood and other bodily fluids for a longer period of time 
than those used in examining patients 
the centers for disease control knows of 20 published cases in 
which a health care worker has been infected with the aids virus on 
the job 
most of these were believed to have been accidental needle 
pricks but at least four were believed to have been infected when 
chapped or scratched skin was exposed to the virus 
