fierce northerly winds wednesday blew a flock of 
arctic seabirds over britain one of the largest movements of 
little auks ever recorded here 
little auks relatives of guillemots and puffins were spotted 
flying in an almost continuous stream off whitburn tyne and wear 
in northeast england near the scottish border 
this is one of the greatest movements of these normally scarce 
visitors to british waters ever recorded said peter collins the 
national trust warden at whitburn 
almost 4000 little auks were spotted in five hours and 
birdwatchers manning whitburn observatory said they may have missed 
many more flying low among the waves 
the birding report came as gales swept the north sea on 
wednesday capsizing a fishing boat with six men aboard 
threatening oil rig crews and driving mountainous waves onto 
britains east coast 
the storm followed weekend snowstorms that buffeted britain and 
much of europe leaving about 20 people dead stranding hundreds of 
travelers and downing power lines supplying thousands of homes 
flood alerts were issued along the east coast on wednesday 
