<TEXT>
the german maker of an antidepressant that 
was sold worldwide said wednesday it will plead guilty to charges 
it waited too long to notify us regulators the drug killed two 
patients in europe 
hoechst ag marketed the drug nomifensine in the united states 
under the name merital and voluntarily pulled it from shelves in 
1986 
the companys us subsidiary hoechstroussel pharmaceuticals 
inc in somerville was not charged a spokeswoman there said the 
german company intended to plead guilty to the charges and pay the 
maximum fine of 202000 a court date has not been set 
the charges were filed wednesday in us district court in 
newark against hoechst ag and its former research director rainer 
zapf 
the case marks the first time a foreign drug maker has been 
prosecuted for failing to inform the food and drug administration 
of adverse drug reactions that occurred outside the united states 
said us attorney michael chertoff 
more than 14 million people in 96 countries used the 
antidepressant between its introduction in the early 1970s until 
it was approved for use in the united states in december 1984 the 
company said hoechst began marketing the drug in the united states 
in july 1985 
charges were filed because hoechst waited until 1986 to inform 
the fda of a 1984 nomifensinerelated death in france and a 1981 
death in italy authorities said 
accurate and timely reports of serious drug complications 
irrespective of where in the world those reactions occur are 
critical to millions of americans who rely on the food and drug 
administration to help ensure that prescribed medications are safe 
and effective chertoff said in a statement 
hoechst pulled the drug after it noticed an increase in 
hemolytic anemia a potentially fatal form of leukemia in which the 
red blood cells that carry oxygen through the body are destroyed 
faster than the body can replace them 
the two patients in europe died from hemolytic anemia associated 
with the drug court papers showed 
andrea stine a spokeswoman for both the parent company and the 
us subsidiary said she did not know how widely the drug was used 
in the united states she said the company recorded 5 million in 
us sales from the antidepressant but she did not know what it 
cost 
rick blumber an attorney for the fda said hoechst acted 
properly when it reported another death associated with the drug in 
europe in april 1985 he said the antidepressant was relabeled as 
a result of that fatality to warn that the drug could cause 
hemolytic anemia 
