<TEXT>
parched by four years of drought southern 
california cities and water agencies face stricter conservation 
measures including mandatory rationing and hefty fines for those 
who fail to comply 
efforts to conserve dwindling water supplies accompany a growing 
fear that winter precipitation wont be enough to stave off a 
devastating fifth year of drought 
wednesday the city councils intergovernmental committee 
approved a proposal to seek statewide water rationing patterned 
after the citys own conservation ordinance the measure must be 
approved by the full council where it is expected to pass easily 
council president john ferraro said 
the board of the metropolitan water district southern 
californias largest water supplier serving about 15 million 
people imposed a strict mandatory rationing plan tuesday on its 
client cities and agencies 
the district serves los angeles orange san diego riverside 
san bernardino and ventura counties 
both actions point to a growing realization that the region is 
running out of water rapidly and that voluntary conservation 
measures may not be enough 
what if next year the drought should continue asked 
metropolitan water district spokesman bob gomperz what weve 
done is weve drawn down reservoir sources of water and now were 
down to the bare bones 
in seeking statewide water rationing los angeles risks 
aggravating a longstanding conflict with northern california over 
