sponsoring legislation because thats so sensitive 
as the shortage develops i think theyll be more receptive 
he said 
no bill has been drafted yet 
under the districts rationing plan water agencies and cities 
must achieve reductions equal to a 5 percent cut in residential use 
and a 20 percent reduction in agricultural use violators will be 
charged triple the usual price for each acrefoot of water over the 
limit an acrefoot is about 326000 gallons 
the district left it to local entities to determine how to 
accomplish the reduction goals 
following the districts action mayor tom bradley said the city 
will look at imposing similar mandatory conservation measures but 
a decision likely will be delayed until february when officials 
can better assess the effect of winter precipitation 
since early this year the city has relied on voluntary 
conservation to achieve a 10 percent reduction in consumption the 
program is part of a conservation plan that calls for restrictions 
that become increasingly strict as they are phased in 
in phase 2 the 10 percent reduction becomes compulsory and 
violators are assessed substantial fines phase 5 the plans final 
segment requires a 25 percent reduction in water use 
san diego another large southern california water consumer has 
no immediate plans to impose mandatory rationing on residents said 
paul downey spokesman for mayor maureen oconnor 
