<TEXT>
a judge has ruled the federal fair housing law 
cannot be applied to insurers rejecting two of five charges 
against an insurance company accused of discriminating against 
black homeowners in milwaukee 
us district court judge stadtmueller on tuesday dismissed two 
of five claims in a class action lawsuit against american family 
mutual insurance co by the naacp 
lawyers for eight black homeowners including milwaukee alderman 
marvin pratt and the national association for the advancement of 
colored people said the decision will be appealed 
the naacp has said it is attempting to apply the federal law 
guaranteeing fair access to housing to providers of homeowners 
insurance because homeowners who cannot get such insurance are 
unable to buy homes 
the case is significant because it addresses a problem that 
has substantial adverse impact on housing in the cities across the 
nation said william lynch a lawyer for the plaintiffs 
the us justice departments civil rights division and the 
national fair housing alliance a washingtonbased advocacy group 
have filed briefs in support of the lawsuit 
the lawsuit claims american family discriminates in a practice 
known as redlining in which insurers instruct agents to avoid 
selling policies in areas with more than 25 percent black 
population 
the lawsuit includes a memo the naacp alleges was written by a 
american family supervisor instructing an insurance agent to stop 
writing those blacks it also alleges the insurer failed to hire 
and retain black agents did not locate offices in black 
neighborhoods and offered blacks less advantageous policies 
than whites 
the two claims dismissed against the company were that 
individuals need court action against the company because state law 
doesnt allow them to take direct action against insurers and that 
it is unlawful for insurers to discriminate against homeowners 
based on location of house 
in dismissing those claims stadtmueller said any discriminatory 
practices by insurance companies could not be considered in 
violation of the us fair housing act 
stadtmueller cited a 1984 decision that said the fair housing 
act enforced by the department of housing and urban development 
was not aimed at insurance agencies 
john powell aclu national legal director disagreed with the 
judge saying other court decisions since 1984 apply the fair 
housing act in lawsuits against insurance companies 
im fairly confident the 7th circuit court of appeals will 
overturn his decision because theyve already spoken and ruled 
fair housing statutes apply to insurance companies he said 
