the denominations open operating style it laid the matter all out 
plainly 
responses ran nearly 3to1 in support of the dissenting 
organization the presbyterian lay committee said the rev james 
v johnson jr chairman of a special committee set up to look into 
the groups ways 
it would be accurate to say that the special committee has 
been very surprised by the breadth and depth of support for the 
group he added 
the presbyterian lay committee based in springfield pa 
consists of an 18member board of directors which puts out a 
bimonthly newspaper the presbyterian layman it reports a 
circulation of 400000 and regularly assails church policies and 
programs 
charging that the denomination supports leftist and socialist 
causes and views the editor j robert campbell said the church 
should stay out of politics and stick to its unique mission 
that is the proclamation of the gospel and making of disciples 
he said in a telephone interview 
he said the church findings mean the denominational leaders 
have refused to listen to people out across the church theres a 
tremendous gap between what the denominational leaders think and 
what the people in the pews think 
victor jameson editor of the denominations monthly 
presbyterian survey based in louisville ky interprets the 
findings quite differently 
our people have a kind of feeling that everybody should have 
their say even if they dont like whats said and even if its 
wrong and ought not to be said he said 
the special committee set up by the churchs 1989 governing 
assembly to check into relationships with the presbyterian lay 
committee solicited responses from the churchatlarge 
sixty percent of about 200 responses considered the criticizing 
group a valuable voice of dissent in the church even though it 
tends to overdo it johnson said 
he said 10 percent supported the paper without reservation and 
30 percent considered it harmful to the church johnson said the 
committee also received more than 6000 preprinted forms 
distributed by the critical group that supported it 
in testimony to johnsons committee elected national assembly 
representatives serving in five program areas charged the lay 
committees paper with errors misstatements and personal attacks 
the 3 millionmember denominations representative assembly 
repeatedly has objected to the groups fundraising methods and 
charged journalistic excesses and unauthorized use of church 
mailing lists 
editor campbell said his group supplied material to john s 
tomkins a presbyterian layman and author of an article in the 
current readers digest sharply critical of his denomination and 
some other protestant bodies 
also credited as a source for the article is the 
washingtonbased institute on religion and democracy a backer of 
conservative causes 
like the critical presbyterian lay organization tomkins charges 
that bureaucrats have taken over the denominations and that a wide 
gulf exists between the bureaucrats and average parishioners 
the rev s david stoner of louisville executive director of 
the presbyterian general assembly council said both the institute 
on religion and democracy and the dissenting presbyterian group 
have strongly political agendas of their own 
he said tomkins has a right and duty to state where he thinks 
the institutional church has erred but those disagreeing have a 
similar duty to clarify the facts 
rebutting the contention that bureaucrats have taken over the 
denominations and are out of touch with church members stoner 
cites the presbyterians democratic processes he said members 
elect their representatives who choose their leaders and said staff 
are hired using carefully set guidelines 
he also challenged tomkins implication that mainline churches 
are losing many members to conservative churches 
scientific surveys conducted in recent years indicate that 
very few former members of mainline churches have left to join 
conservative churches he said most members who leave are lost 
not to conservatism but to nonaffiliation with any church 
the special presbyterian committee set up to consult with the 
dissenting group and discuss its asserted refusal to comply with 
denominational guidelines for special organizations is to make its 
final report to the 1991 assembly in june 
johnson said some things his committee learned so far are 
there is a widespread feeling in the church that the 
criticizing group performs a useful function as a dissenting 
voice but many who see its value have questioned its 
journalistic tactics 
there is a compelling need for the church to work for 
reconciliation among various factions in the church who do not 
trust and are afraid of each other 
