the long list of photography books this year 
ranges from the 13th collection of photojournalism by lifes alfred 
eisenstaedt now 91 to the very edge of the photography as art 
debate with the works of the 29yearold starn twins 
in between there are many familiar names with elegies to 
western photographer ansel adams to photographer and filmmaker 
paul strand and to robert mapplethorpe 
but 1990 also reflected an increasing awareness for the work of 
women and of conceptual photographers 
women photographers harry n abrams 65 provides a full 
survey of women photographers they include pioneers such as julia 
margaret cameron and gertrude kasebier and emerging work such as 
the startlig documentary shots from central america of susan 
meiselas and the conceptual art of jan groover 
lisette model university of chicago press 3596 is among 
the best of the books on individual photographers it is the 
catalog for an exhibit that opened in ottawa this fall the first 
major retrospective on one of this centurys most innovative 
photographers and effective teachers whose pupils included such 
luminaries as diane arbus the text which takes great pains to 
demystify model an often intentionally baffling pesonality is as 
enjoyable as the photographs of the odd assortment of characters on 
whom she focused her camera 
cindy shermans untitled stills rizzoli 3750 is a 
collection of her works from the 1970s when she made a tremendous 
splash with her concept of photographing herself in hollywoodstyle 
poses she has since moved on to other things but her stills 
remain a provocative case study in postmodern art well treated in 
the lucid introductory essay by philosopher arthur danto 
lucia moholy florence henri and other women get fair notice in 
photography at the bauhaus mit press 75 it is a sweeping 
work with elaborate essays and about 450 photographs covering every 
phase of the exciting and important experimental art movement of 
the 20s and early 30s with biographies on all of the artists 
of the place books the best are of historic interest and are by 
women including photographing montana 18941928 alfred 
knopf 60 a look at the old west through the eyes of evelyn 
cameron a britisher to the manor born who fell for the big sky 
country during a visit and decided to stay 
published last year but on a slow journey to bookshelves is 
eudora welty photographs university of mississippi press 
50 offering scenes from the south by a writer who has been one 
of its most distinctive chroniclers for 50 years her photography 
has especially strong documentary value because of her penchant 
even as far back as the 30s to focus so often on ordinary 
citizens 
also noteworthy both for content and as a look at a good 
personal collection of photographs is nancy hathaways native 
american portraits 18621918 chronicle books 1695 these 
portraits riveting as a sad chronicle of the indians during their 
demise is from new york attorney kurt koeglers collection 
werner bischof bulfinch press 65 is a testament to the 
swiss photojournalist who died young in 1954 the book includes his 
famous life photo essay on famine in india and work from china 
japan and indochina it also includes his wellwritten 
correspondences telling of a young photographers battle to 
maintain integrity while feeding a world market hungry for shots of 
exotic suffering 
bischofs appearance seems so timely given the continued current 
attention to sebastiao salgado whose work in south america hints 
at the kinds of shots bischof and others who worked for robert capa 
in the 1940s might have taken salgados an uncertain grace 
aperture 60 is largely made up of powerful scenes of 
deprivation 
gentler is ansel adams the american wilderness it is 
published by bulfinch with 146 pages and 107 duotones in 
impressive large format that give his vistas more the scope they 
deserve but at 100 it is an expensive look 
equally costly is the fine retrospective on paul strand put out 
by aperture and the national gallery of art which catalogs a show 
that opened at the national gallery this month and travels over the 
next two years to chicago st louis houston new york san 
francisco and london 
strand always a reluctant printer of his own works teamed with 
richard benson to produce a project of prints completed as he lay 
dying at his home in france it must have been painful for him but 
given the paucity of his prints that were extant the project made 
for both a fine show on the centenary of strands birth and an 
important archive 
robert mapplethorpes flowers bulfinch 50 might be the 
final chapter for some time in the career of the man who drew wider 
attention to photography in a shorter time than almost anyone 
before him the photographs are lovely in their technical 
production and in their startling sensuality as his friend patti 
smith indicates in her introduction mapplethorpe was the lily and 
the orchid but also their sinister shadow 
the most pleasingly different approaches are an anglers 
album fishing in photography and12 0626 
 
