<TEXT>
this is the first in an occasional series 
examining the changing family 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
on mondays it was meatloaf with string beans and a baked 
potato the ritual evening meal usually served around 630 or so 
was alive with laughter and the inevitable family squabbles 
the arguments generally were settled before the dinner hour 
rolled around again what lingered were memories of the corny 
jokes a little parental wisdom perhaps the brief quiet after 
grace was said 
dinner time in america conjures images of the hearth the nest 
family members gather around the table to share their lives and 
perhaps learn a little from one another 
thats the snapshot we hold its the way families are supposed 
to be but the idyll of regular warm togetherness at the table 
often doesnt work out 
the nuclear family of yesteryear has in many cases splintered 
today more than half of mothers hold down jobs outside the home 
kids too are busier than ever with afterschool sports and other 
activities 
all too often the dinner hour is fast food inhaled in front of 
the television set instead of around a table set with silverware 
and napkins 
yet recent polls have shown the vast majority of americans make 
an effort to dine together regularly parents recognize that 
mealtime often is the only real chance family members have to get 
involved in each others lives 
we are all caught between reality and the expectation of 
leave it to beaver where everyone sits around the table and 
makes chirpy conversation said susan ginsberg editor of work amp 
family life newsletter 
the reality is that we are all so busy that we find it hard to 
sit down together said ginsberg who also directs work and 
family programs at bank street college in new york we have less 
time than we did 25 years ago 
but most parents believe dining together should be a priority 
it encourages openness helps kids develop conversational skills 
strengthens the family unit 
the goal of dinner time is not to sit silently and eat said 
thomas weisner an anthropologist at the university of 
californialos angeles the goal is to share knowledge and 
information reaffirm cultural values 
weisner and eleanor ochs a linguist and colleague at ucla 
spent three years studying videotapes of mealtimes in 20 los 
angeles households struggling to preserve the dinner hour amid 
modern lifes competing demands 
the most important thing that we found was that regardless of 
socieconomics or the dinner arrangements all the families used the 
time to talk about problems and problemsolving ochs said 
its a nice scenario the image of loving parents brothers and 
sisters participating in each others lives 
but dont despair if dinner table conversation at your house 
tends more toward complaints about undercooked spaghetti and 
sibling taunts and blowups over grades chores or next years 
family vacation destination 
we all have this fantasy about the perfect dinner said 
ellen galinsky of the families and work institute of new york 
then you sit down and nobody likes the food or people fight 
 
you feel really rotten because you think that at other 
peoples houses theyre having discussions about the election or 
coming recession or some other meaningful topic said galinsky 
who conducts parenting seminars 
the fact is family dinner hours dont always make for erudite 
conversation sometimes they are raucous or downright rocky but 
thats all right the experts say what counts is the act of 
sitting down of setting time aside 
june and tom darlings seven children know that their memories 
differ but all hold close the chaos that was dinner time at their 
home the almosta ranch in southern michigan 
having rituals is important said the familys 71yearold 
matriarch ours was a big round table with two extra leaves it 
could easily sit 10 and we all knew when daddy got home it was 
time to gather round 
the darling childrens lives have veered far from that 1950s 
tableau they now are adults with kids of their own and like much 
of america they struggle to keep family tradition alive despite 
lifes complications 
we need to make choices here said janice darling one of 
five daughters who all went on to become mothers we need to 
sacrifice a few things so we have a little calm in our lives time 
to enjoy each other 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901212-0192 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
theyve come to cherish a whole childhoods worth of dinners 
shared around a solid maple table near an open kitchen hearth but 
tom and june darlings seven kids have branched out in seven 
directions making new traditions for themselves in their own 
homes 
theirs are the dinner tables of today 
the eldest nancy darling hutchinson of houston with her 
husband raised three sons who are starting families of their own 
the youngest tom and michael run the family hardware store in 
marshall mich they make it home for dinner pretty much every 
night the way their father did 
in between are the four middle daughters who like so many 
parents across america are carving new traditions from a family 
legacy 
heres a glimpse of how the darlings dinner time ritual has 
evolved 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
janice darlings variety store is nestled among the twinkling 
lights and garlands that festoon main street all of marshall 
mich seems to be in the oldfashioned holiday spirit 
its the time of year when janice feels slightly nostalgic a 
little mournful for old times like dinner with her parents and six 
brothers and sisters gathered round 
its also the time of year the single mother keeps her shop open 
seven days a week instead of the usual six the time of year when 
life is even more frenetic than usual 
dinner is the first thing to go said janice 44 who is 
struggling to adapt the 1950s traditions she and her siblings knew 
growing up to the realities of todays changeable world 
theres just no time she said i would like to be home 
around 530 and have dinner all ready turn off the tv and just sit 
and talk just chat i miss that 
but janices 15yearold daughter jennifer needs to be at band 
practice she plays clarinet or swim team shes got a great 
freestyle stroke or the library a book report is due 
and janice who works 70hour weeks needs to get back to 
darling amp daughter the dime store she runs for her father 
dinner is generally a fastfood affair hamburgers pizza or 
takeout chicken wolfed down in front of the evening news or most 
often en route somewhere 
we have our mealtime in the car thats our time together 
janice said you spill stuff down your front but no matter what 
were still getting in touch 
janice and her daughter have traditions theyre just not 
traditional traditions their rituals are tailored to a single mom 
and daughter whose lives and needs cant be scripted 
dinner time at my house it very unruly it makes me feel bad 
that we dont have enough time to sit and listen to each other 
janice said it cant be but i long for the days when you sat on 
the front porch rocking and watching your neighbors walk by 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
on just about any evening youll find gail darling morgan her 
husband and three children gathered for dinner at their twostory 
home in west palm beach fla 
they use cloth napkins and placemats the atmosphere generally 
is calm and the discussions a bit civilized it probably wont 
last 
her kids will be teenagers in a few short years 
but right now my kids are still young said gail 39 
theres a six or sevenyear period where theyre accepting of 
whatever is put in front of them before they become 
sophisticated and busy 
already gails elder two kids by a previous marriage are 
beginning to participate in sports and join afterschool clubs 
