<TEXT>
bank earnings are headed down and wont 
reverse course until the economy emerges from its slump analysts 
say 
the federal deposit insurance corp said tuesday that the 
nations 12399 commercial banks earned 375 billion in the 
julyseptember quarter down 29 percent from 54 billion in the 
econd quarter banks earned 63 billion in the first three months 
of the year 
fdic chairman l william seidman blamed the deterioration on a 
rise in sour real estate loans particularly in the northeast he 
described the outlook for the final three months of the year as 
bleak and declined to predict when bank earnings would recover 
the problem will drag on just as long as the economy is in 
whatever its in now seidman said i wont say the rword 
he said referring to the bush administrations reluctance to 
describe the economic downturn as a recession 
economist paul getman of regional financial associates in west 
chester pa said i wish i could say its going to get better 
but its going to get worse before it gets better 
seidman warned that banks problems are translating into 
mounting strain on the government insurance fund protecting bank 
deposits 
he raised his estimate of the fdic funds 1990 loss from 3 
billion to 4 billion or more and said it was becoming 
increasingly clear that banks will have to inject more money 
into the fund 
the loss would leave only 9 billion to protect 2 trillion in 
deposits 
were probably under more pressure in the banking system than 
we have been at any time since the 1930s said economist david 
jones of aubrey g lanston amp co id look for continued strains 
on the system in general 
jones said the health of the economy and of banking are 
deteriorating in a vicious circle slumping economic conditions 
create loan losses for banks that causes banks to cut back 
lending which fuels the economic slump 
still 89 percent of commercial banks made money in the third 
quarter the profitability of small banks those with less than 
100 million in assets suffered only slightly but problems in 
larger institutions in the east dragged down the industry totals 
banks posted losses in the district of columbia and eight 
states arizona connecticut maine maryland massachusetts new 
hampshire new jersey and new york 
delinquent real estate loans in which borrowers are three 
months or more behind on their payments rose 129 percent to 313 
billion in the third quarter 
the real estate delinquency rate was highest in rhode island 
1466 percent followed by arizona massachusetts connecticut 
texas oklahoma new hampshire louisiana new york the district 
of columbia new jersey new mexico and colorado 
however the rate was headed down in the southwestern states and 
up in the east 
getman noted that recent weakness in west coast real estate 
markets has yet to surface in bank data the other shoe has yet 
to drop and the other shoe is california he said 
consumer loan delinquencies also are rising they were up 104 
percent to 14 billion in the third quarter getman predicted that 
as the recession progresses credit card delinquencies will emerge 
as the next big area of concern to bankers 
for the first time the fdic issued a report on the 479 savings 
banks it supervises these statechartered institutions a hybrid 
of a commercial bank and a savings institution are located 
primarily in the northeast and concentrate on real estate lending 
even more than commercial banks 
they lost 771 million during the third quarter during the 
first nine months of the year 35 percent of the savings banks lost 
money and as a whole lost 12 billion compared with 20 million 
in earnings during the same period of 1989 
however they remain well capitalized on average their owners 
investment represented 702 percent of the savings banks assets 
capital acts as a cushion between losses and the insurance fund 
