<TEXT>
some 2000 companies in former east germany will 
be able to keep their export markets in the soviet union and other 
east european countries under measures announced wednesday 
exports to the rublebased trading bloc were economic mainstays 
of east germany before it united with west germany in october but 
the conversion to the west german mark threatens to put an end to 
such business depriving wobbly economies in the east of their 
traditional source of modern equipment 
german economists say hundreds of thousands of jobs in eastern 
germany depend on continuation of exports to the east 
officials of the treuhandanstalt the trust agency charged with 
disposing of most of the former stateowned assets of east germany 
said the governmentbacked hermes export insurance agency will 
support under certain conditions new contracts that companies in 
eastern germany are able to make with soviet or other east european 
customers 
the contracts must be in hard currency and the treuhand will 
have to verify that the german companies are making progress toward 
the efficiency standards of the freemarket economy wolfram 
krause the treuhands finance director told a news conference 
many companies in former east germany that the treuhand hopes to 
privatize face a deadline of jan 1 to convert longterm contracts 
from the inconvertible soviet ruble into hard currency 
the german government is backing 108 billion worth of such 
rubledenominated eastbound exports in 1990 krause said that 
support expires at the end of this year but the new export 
insurance will help to continue the valuable direction of business 
the companies will be more attractive to purchasers he said 
adding we know that this is the time to sell 
what makes eastern germany so attractive for investment is 
this is the only country in the world where you have two directions 
of the economy said treuhand spokesman thomas schneider west 
germany has the western direction and east germany has the eastern 
direction if you are looking for a new market it will be in the 
east 
eastern german companies will only be attractive in the future 
if they retain their markets in the east he said and the export 
insurance measure was one way to support such business 
