<TEXT>
the european community commission said 
wednesday it had extended for two years its controls over state 
subsidies to the beleaguered auto industry in the ecs 12 member 
states 
the commissions authority to bar large state awards to car 
manufacturers is crucial to ensure that a climate of normal and 
fair competition prevails as the industry approaches an uncertain 
future the commission said in a statement 
the commissions 2yearold framework says all state subsidies 
exceeding 12 million european currency units or 164 million 
must be approved by the ecs executive commission 
the commission said it fears that current intense competition in 
the ec auto industry could push some member states into approving 
huge subsidies if the commissions powers to curb state aids were 
ended 
separately the ec allowed france to fund 40 percent of a 240 
million research project between car makers renault and peugeot for 
fuelefficient automobiles with cleanburning engines 
the commission said it approved french aid of about 97 million 
for the eightyear project which will involve several research 
organizations and focus on cleanburning engines development of a 
new twostroke engine and electric and gaspowered vehicles 
the commission said the framework on member subsidies was vital 
in preparing for a unified motor vehicle market once the trade bloc 
unifies after 1992 
it said clamping down on huge state subsidies was the best 
guarantee that the industry will be able to improve its 
competitiveness on world markets 
ec demand for cars in 1990 and 1991 is expected to decline 
before returning to a longerterm annual growth of 1 percent a 
year the commission said 
it said the uneertain outlook for the industry as a whole adds 
to the case for vigilance in the control of state aids 
</TEXT>
