<DOCNO> AP901212-0230 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the official november job report was one of the 
bleakest in many years further documenting the process by which 
elements of a sliding economy reinforce each other and lead to 
recession 
depicted graphically it would look like a rube goldberg 
contraption in which one action generates another and another and 
another the end result being nothing produced but a waste of time 
energy and capital 
in terms of a sliding economy you might begin with big debts 
and tight money which lead to lower consumer and business 
spending which produces lower profits income strains and layoffs 
forcing further spending cuts 
viewed in that sense the consequences of the terrible november 
job report become clear fewer workers working fewer hours means 
less money for retailers who cut their orders to wholesalers and 
wholesalers who cut jobs and spending 
there was almost no good news in the report delivered by janet 
norwood commissioner of the bureau of labor statistics 
in her own words 
employment declined sharply and the declines were widespread 
throughout both the goods and the service sectors of the economy 
the unemployment rate rose from 57 percent to 59 percent the 
rate is now more than 05 percent higher than it was in the first 
half of the year 
the number of payroll jobs declined sharply for the second 
month in a row a reduction of 265000 jobs in november followed a 
loss of 180000 in october we have not had consecutive job losses 
of this magnitude since the end of 1982 
threequarers of the november reduction occurred in the 
already weak manufacturing industry nearly 800000 factory jobs 
have been dropped since january 1989 
even servicesector jobs were affected jobs in retail trades 
fell by 70000 wholesale trade employment fell sharply and as 
has been well publicized big losses occurred in the real estate 
and finance industries 
the one piece of news that might be construed as positive really 
wasnt employment in the health services industry rose by 80000 
jobs bringing to more than 600000 the number of jobs added in 
that category within a year 
why isnt that good news for those who found employment it was 
of course good news but for the rest of us it was ominous health 
service spending has been out of control for years each year it 
consumes more of the gross national product each year its 
inflation rate exceeds that of the general economy 
how can the deterioration be changed in the old days you primed 
the pump with government spending but government already is 
spending too much because of that an unusually large role falls 
to the federal reserve 
the fed can do its part in a number of ways such as easing 
credit restraints putting more money into the economy and allowing 
interest rates to fall 
so far it hasnt done a great deal in that respect in the 
past chairman alan greenspan has espoused a goal of zero 
inflation and inflation for the current quarter might be 6 percent 
not terribly bad but not zero 
greenspan is one of the most dedicated antiinflationists ever 
to sit as fed chairman he has sound reasons for fearing it 
considering the amount of debt already existing the dollars value 
and the fragile financial system 
but that november jobless report not just the increases in 
joblessness but the speeding up of the process might force him to 
forgo the pursuit of zero inflation and get more americans back to 
work 
</TEXT>
