<TEXT>
hollis harris built a reputation in the airline 
industry as an easygoing executive with an optimistic cheerleading 
management style 
when he left delta air lines inc in august after 36 years 
harris seemed to be just what continental airlines inc needed 
someone with the financial savvy to keep the carrier afloat and an 
exuberant personality to encourage dispirited employees 
it may sound a little corny but i say continental team 
lets go get them he told employees when he was introduced as 
chairmanelect 
but harris will have to use all those spirited traits and more 
if hes to see continental through chapter 11 federal bankruptcy 
proceedings 
the nations fifthlargest carrier filed for protection from 
creditors earlier this month citing soaring fuel costs and 
mounting interest payments on its 62 billion debt it was 
continentals second bankrutpcy filing 
harris predecessor frank lorenzo built continental through a 
series of mergers and acquisitions over nearly two decades but he 
incurred the wrath of union workers during the first reorganization 
in 1983 when he insinuated greedy unions were hurting the company 
harris has painstakenly tried to avoid such confrontations 
our 37000 employees have earned a reputation for working hard 
and smart while providing american travelers with the services they 
need he remarked following the companys bankruptcy filing 
announcement 
harris still commuting from his home in georgia was 
unavailable for an interview continental officials said 
harris has said he sees his role as part of a leadership 
continuum for the company and believes his job is to make the 
airline run more smoothly lorenzos role he said was building 
the airline 
in the 80s people were concentrating more on growing now 
the focus is on competing with service he said 
in four months the 58yearold harris has endeared himself to 
his employees 
mr harris is a very positive peopleoriented person which is 
something we havent known a lot of around continental for 
awhile said pilot robert finley it seems like a breath of 
fresh air to see a man like him in that job 
if anyone can pull us through these difficult times where 
fuel costs are skyrocketing and all costs are elevating at an 
enormous rate while the fares are still being depressed and the 
fare wars are going on i think mr harris is the guy who can do 
it 
friends and associates had equally kind words 
hes a very likeable person i cant remember anybody saying 
anything unkind about him said clara bailey who graduated high 
school with harris in 1949 in carrollton ga about 55 miles west 
of atlanta 
ms bailey who keeps in touch with harris and his wife fellow 
carrollton native joyce harris said the continental leader has 
always been a private person who cared about others 
the son of the rev cl harris a retired methodist minister 
harris excelled in school but ms bailey said he never flaunted 
his achievements 
he was one of the most intelligent people in the class but he 
was also the most unassuming she said 
harris holds a bachelor of aeronautical engineering degree from 
the georgia institute of technology the father of two sons and a 
daughter he gained a reputation in atlanta for his involvement in 
several community projects including the boy scouts of america 
harris was instrumental in setting up a fundraising system for 
the council that provided about 200000 for the group last year 
alone 
harris remains active in other civic activities he serves on 
the advisory council of the national multiple sclerosis society and 
was past chairman of the american institute of aeronautics and 
astronautics among others 
harris joined delta in 1954 as a transportation agent in the 
marketing division and later became an aircraft engineer 
eventually rising to head of that department he subsequently 
served in key management roles in the facilities department 
inflight service passenger service and operations 
harris was named president of delta in 1987 and was responsible 
for all marketing operations technical operations and personnel 
functions 
he was very much liked here said one former employee who 
asked not to be named and his hometown and georgia were very 
proud of him im sure houston and texas will be as well 
</TEXT>
