<TEXT>
how merry christmas 1990 will be depends on 
economic and geographic basics what you do for a living and where 
you do it but it also depends on some intangibles like luck 
timing and creativity the following vignettes reported by ap 
writers jonathan yenkin in boston steven p rosenfeld in des 
moines gry eriksen in los angeles marc rice in atlanta and joyce 
m rosenberg in new york look at the holiday season from a variety 
of vantage points 
equals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
homers jewelry store sits in the heart of bostons downtown 
shopping district and like the holiday seasons of years past the 
aisles are crammed with people who peer into glass cases and try on 
gold bracelets 
but this scene does not sparkle like it normally would for store 
manager donald cohen 
after 108 years in business homers is holding one last sale 
before closing its doors becoming another casualty of hard times 
in new england 
this is the only place i ever worked said cohen 55 who 
first came to the shop as an errand boy in 1950 its going to be 
quite different after 40 years getting up each day and coming to 
work here 
homers is a virtual landmark in boston but its fate is not so 
unique the massachusetts economy sinking into recession for more 
than a year has forced thousands of people out of work 
that gave may retailers a dim outlook for this christmas 
season jewelers find it is difficult to sell gold and diamonds to 
people keeping a close eye on their wallets 
we have so many people coming in talking about relatives 
losing their jobs said cohen its more important that they 
have food on their table 
with business declining homers owners decided to close down 
now rather than watch the shop sink further 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
equals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
for iowa farm wife debbie hardersen spending 60 on a blouse 
and skirt is unusually extravagant 
but the clothes were on sale and times are good if not great 
for farmers so she bought the outfit for herself on a shopping 
spree recently during the iowa farm bureau convention 
i didnt feel too badly buying it hardersen said 
ive spent 350 here and im not done yet she said 
christmas is a time i do like to splurge 
theres no scrimping or pinching pennies this year 
iowa manufacturers such as winnebago industries inc and deere amp 
co may be laying off workers this fall as sales slump but the 
farm economy is on the mend from the freefall of the 1980s 
hardersen 36 went to the convention with her husband don 41 
their two children stayed at their home outside the eastern iowa 
community of anamosa where the couple farms 600 acres and raises 
hogs and cattle 
cattle prices were at alltime highs during convention week and 
hog prices remained comfortably above the breakeven point while 
corn and soybean prices have been slumping the crop was good and 
cheap feed grains reduce the expense of raising livestock 
overall the mood out in the country is much more 
optimistic debbie hardersen says 
</TEXT>
