<TEXT>
the federal governments inaction against mortgage lenders with 
excessive amounts held in escrow forced legal action against the 
gmac mortgage corp attorneys general in six states said 
wednesday 
attorneys general in iowa california massachusetts minnesota 
new york and texas filed the suit wednesday in us district court 
for the southern district of new york 
gmac mortgage corp of detroit and several of its subsidiaries 
routinely hold in these mortgage accounts more funds than either 
federal law or the homeowners mortgage contracts allow the 
lawsuit alleges 
the suit would bar gmacs illegal practice of requiring excess 
money to be held in homeowners mortgage escrow accounts 
massachusetts attorney general james m shannon said in a statement 
wednesday 
gmac will take appropriate action to defend against the 
allegations in the suit said rick gillespie a gmac vice president 
in elkins park pa 
gmac mortgage corp is confident it has been and remains in 
full compliance with federal and state laws and industry practices 
and that these practices are fair to each consumer and our 
company gillespie said he said the corporation voluntarily gave 
information to the attorneys general to aid their research gmac 
has about 400000 residential mortgages nationwide 
escrow accounts are kept by lending institutions to make 
payments for property taxes insurance and other items that 
borrowers must pay extra money in escrow is a bonanza for lenders 
because they can use the money for free or pay only a low rate of 
interest on it 
about twothirds of the nations home mortgages involve escrow 
accounts 
federal law limits lenders to keeping a twomonth cushion in 
escrow or enough money to make payments for two months the 
cushion allows lenders to make tax and insurance payments even if 
the consumer is late making a monthly payment 
in april the attorneys general issued a report critical of the 
practice of requiring excess money in the accounts they asked 
housing and urban development secretary jack kemp to tighten 
enforcement of the escrow law 
when we released the report of the illegal escrow practices of 
gmac and other lenders we urged the federal government to enforce 
its own statutory limits on escrow payments so far it has taken 
no action thus prompting suits like the one filed today at great 
cost to the states new york attorney general robert abrams said 
our report estimated that the excess cushion averages about 
150 per homeowner iowa attorney general thomas miller said 
that means we think lenders are holding several billion dollars 
that should be in the hands of their customers 
the twoyear study said consumers were being overcharged 2 
billion to 4 billion by the nations mortgage lenders 
the study focused on big lenders who operate nationwide a 
survey of four of the largest citibank gmac mortgage corp 
fleet mortgage corp and lomas financial group indicated that 
lenders may be holding excessive and illegal cushions in more than 
70 percent of escrow accounts 
bob brammer an administrative assistant in the iowa attorney 
generals office said inquiries still are being made into escrow 
practices of the other lenders 
we dont contemplate any lawsuits regarding them in the 
immediate future brammer said 
massachusetts assistant attorney general ernest sarason who 
handled the suit for shannon said the states have been studying 
the issue for more than two years 
the reason that we filed the suit is that we were very 
concerned about mortgage companies not complying with federal law 
limiting the amount of mortgage escrow sarason said 
</TEXT>
