<TEXT>
opec will continue pumping oil at high 
levels to offset crude losses caused by the persian gulf crisis 
officials said late wednesday 
indonesian oil minister ginandjar kartasasmita said the 13 
nations of the organization of petroleum exporting countries would 
sign a statement thursday endorsing continued increased production 
he said in an interview that they also would promise to reduce 
their output to levels set in late july once the gulf crisis has 
ended 
in august after iraq invaded kuwait the cartel temporarily 
suspended its quota system to permit higher pumping by nations with 
spare capacity 
we will continue with the august agreement ginandjar said 
we are reaffirming everything said gabonese oil minister 
jean ping 
the august accord was put together so that heavyweight saudi 
arabia and other producing nations could make up for lost iraqi and 
kuwaiti crude 
about 4 million barrels of oil a day have been pulled from the 
market because of international sanctions imposed after iraq 
invaded kuwait aug 2 
ginandjar said that when the gulf troubles subside the cartel 
would reimpose the output caps in force in late july under that 
accord all 13 nations agreed to hold production to 225 million 
barrels a day in an effort to reach a target of 21 dollars a 
barrel 
the cartels current production is pegged at around 23 million 
barrels a day saudi arabia the worlds largest crude exporter is 
close to pumping 85 million barrels a day sources have said its 
quota under the july accord was 54 million barrels 
other members pumping above their previous levels are venezuela 
nigeria the united arab emirates iran and libya 
the ministers who agreed to meet again in early march made 
their decisions during five hours of formal and informal talks on 
the opening day of their winter strategy session 
it was the first time since the invasion that all 13 
oilproducing representatives have been represented iraq and libya 
did not attend the meeting at which the cartels quota system was 
suspended 
no sparks were reported between iraq and kuwait seated next to 
each other in the conference rooms alphabetical arrangement 
ramzi salman abdul hussain director of iraqs state oil 
marketing organization said little but he told reporters that 
iraq could increase its crude production to strong levels as soon 
as we want 
none of the facilities are damaged he said 
iraq is estimated to be producing a mere 400000 barrels a day 
compared to earlier levels of more than 3 million barrels 
rasheed salem alameeri the oil minister for kuwaits 
governmentinexile also insisted his country could get its oil 
industry back to former levels quickly with a peaceful resolution 
he said iraqi invaders have done extensive damage to our oil 
industry but we have plans to reconstruct it in a short 
time 
earlier in the day opec president sadek boussena opened the 
strategy session by criticizing oilconsuming nations for failing 
to do much to ease the oil crunch 
instead of tapping crude in their inventories he said the rich 
nations appeared to have added oil to their storage tanks in case 
of a worsening of gulf troubles 
as a result he said opec has been forced into extreme levels 
of output 
this is clearly an illcontrived move boussena the 
algerian mines minister told his counterparts 
if such an escalation does not occur and as we all hope an 
early peaceful solution is found to the crisis then the world 
will be awash with oil he said 
he warned that opec would be faced with another decade of 
turmoil like the rollercoaster 1980s 
nobody in our organization wants a repetition of that era of 
rampant instability said boussena 
the cartel has been in disarray since the gulf crisis after the 
invasion ministers agreed to lift their production caps to offset 
the loss of crude from iraq and kuwait 
the result has been a flood of oil on the market and sharp 
swings in prices 
prices for light sweet crude peaked in october at 41 a barrel 
they since have skidded to under 30 a barrel on hints of peace in 
the middle east and worries about an oil glut 
the average price of a basket of crudes monitored by the cartel 
was 2625 a barrel monday well above its target price of 21 a 
barrel set in july 
opec members are algeria ecuador gabon indonesia iran 
iraq kuwait libya nigeria qatar saudi arabia the united arab 
emirates and venezuela 
</TEXT>
