<TEXT>
a german manufacturer of an antidepressant 
drug that was sold worldwide said wednesday it will plead guilty to 
charges that it waited too long to notify us regulators that the 
medication killed two patients in europe 
hoechst ag marketed the drug nomifensine in the united states 
under the name merital and voluntarily pulled it from shelves in 
1986 
the charges were filed wednesday in us district court in 
newark against hoechst and its former research director rainer 
zapf who will not be extradited to the united states prosecutors 
said 
the companys us subsidiary hoechstroussel pharmaceuticals 
inc based in somerville was not charged 
a court date for the plea has not been set 
us attorney michael chertoff said the case marked the first 
time a foreign drug maker has been prosecuted for failing to inform 
the us food and drug administration of adverse drug reactions 
that occurred outside the united states 
more than 14 million people in 96 countries used the 
antidepressant from its introduction in the early 1970s to its 
approval for use in the united states in december 1984 the company 
said hoechst began marketing the drug in the united states in july 
1985 
charges were filed because hoechst waited until 1986 to inform 
the fda of a 1984 nomifensinerelated death in france and a 1981 
death in italy authorities said 
hoechst pulled the drug from the market after it noticed an 
increase in hemolytic anemia in certain users a potentially fatal 
form of leukemia the two patients in europe died from hemolytic 
anemia associated with the drug according to court papers 
andrea stine a spokeswoman for the company said she did not 
know how widely the drug was used in the united states she said 
hoechst recorded 5 million in us sales from the antidepressant 
fda attorney rick blumber said hoechst acted properly when it 
reported another death associated with the drug in europe in april 
1985 he said the antidepressant was relabeled as a result of that 
fatality 
